## Content
````
The provided source code file, `program.cs`, implements a basic AI agent using various Azure and Model Context Protocol (MCP) services. Designed primarily to interact with and answer questions about GitHub repositories, this sample file showcases the integration of Microsoft and Azure technologies to build and deploy an artificial intelligence agent capable of understanding and executing specific tasks.

The main purpose and functionality of the code revolve around the creation and utilization of an AI agent. Initially, it loads essential environment variables (lines 12-13) for setting up the Azure OpenAI endpoint and deployment name. The default deployment, if not explicitly provided, is set to `gpt-4o-mini`. Critical components involved include the instantiation of an `McpClient` (lines 15-21), which connects to a GitHub server using the Model Context Protocol framework, and the facilitation of tool retrieval from this server (line 24). Once tools are obtained, the code constructs an `AIAgent` (lines 26-30) using the method `CreateAIAgent`, instructing it specifically to address queries related to GitHub repositories.

Structurally, the code follows a sequence beginning with loading environment configurations, establishing server-client connections, and creating and configuring an AI agent. The `McpClient.CreateAsync` method asynchronously starts a connection to the MCP-server using `StdioClientTransport`. This sets up the transport layer with parameters like `Command` and `Arguments` pointing to execution of the server (lines 16-21). The agent itself is instantiated as an `AzureOpenAIClient` object, using credentials obtained from `Azure.Identity.AzureCliCredential`, and utilizes a chat client retrieved by calling `GetChatClient(deploymentName)`. The agent is then configured with specific instructions and linked tools.

Interactions and dependencies within this file are significant and primarily revolve around three main libraries: `Azure.AI.OpenAI` for OpenAI functionalities, `ModelContextProtocol.Client` for interacting with the GitHub server, and `Azure.Identity` for managing credentials. These libraries facilitate integration with external systems, allowing seamless data flow across the client-server architecture. The MCP and Azure services together ensure stability, with asynchronous methods (`await` keyword) enhancing scalability by preventing blocking operations.

Important parameters notably include `AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT`, which must be set within the environment for the code to execute correctly, as its absence throws an exception (`InvalidOperationException`). The `deploymentName` parameter defines the specific model variant of OpenAI to utilize, which affects the agent's responsiveness and operational focus depending on the tasks deployed. By managing these elements effectively, the overall system can maintain functionality while showcasing extensibility in AI-related operations.
````
